column168: A shipment of hazardous waste was being loaded onto a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility at the intermediate truck transfer facility.  The blade of the forklift inadvertantly punctured the bottom of the drum which was on a pallet, causing some of the thick liquid waste to leak.  After donning the appropriate personal protective equipment, the driver uprighted the drum and overpacked it into a suitable salvage drum, along with the absorbant pads used to contain and clean up the spilled material from the dock area.  The shipment was then loaded without further incident.
column169: The driver was cautioned to slow down and be more aware of his surroundings.  The blades of the forklift were not positioned properly for the pallet to clear the lip on the back of the trailer, causing the incident.

column168: Transport vehicle was traveling northbound on FM3733 approximately 1 mile of Muenster, TX, and entered a curve in the roadway in excess of the posted speed limit causing the vehicle to overturn.  As a result of the overturned trailer unit, a crack in a weld seam failed resulting in a release of petroleum crude oil. The City of Muenster immediately deployed a backhoe to contain the leaking material from the transport trailer.  The company notified an environmental response company which deployed a vacuum truck to capture the released material.
column169: Incident information regarding this incident will be communicated to all company drivers, along with emphasis placed on posted speed limits.  Defensive driving program will also be reviewed.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Valve Open
column168: Tank car MBLX 34060 was reported emanating a commodity odor in the railyard. Immediate inspection by BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders revealed the A-end liquid valve was partially open with ice accumulation around its closure plug. The A-end liquid valve was closed (1 1/2 turns to close) and then its non-tool tight closure plug was removed. The plug threads were cleaned and new tape sealant applied. The closure plug was reinserted and tool tightened. Afterwards, no vapors or commodity odor were detectable. Intact shipper seal EXXONMOBIL 004032 at the valve housing cover was replaced with seal BNSF 06157739. MBLX 34060's side specification stencil indicated that its last tank qualification was completed in the year 2010.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On 4 Sep 2013, at 1745, personnel in the CSXT Tilford Yard discovered UTLX200331, a loaded tank car of Heptanes leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and Citgo, CSX HazMat, HEPACO, Atlanta 911, Ga EPD, Chemtrec and NRC were notified.  CHEMTREC Report #2013-0904-00271. HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a loose packing gland and nut on the liquid valve handle stem. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Jon Day, 630-257-4239. Contractor personnel tightened the packing nut and gland and cleaned up the remining liquids that had not already evaporated. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 required? No    Cause Code:  NARRI: 5(5+3+0) x (2+0)= 80

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Tank car GATX 19051 was reported expelling commodity from its top fitting area during normal switching operations in the railyard. Movement was stopped and GATX 19051 was cordoned-off with no further commodity release observed. Contract responders inspecting GATX 19051 reported the spillage on its tank shell emanated from its Midland 75 psi pressure relief valve (PRV). This reclosing PRV sustained a broken stem and responders clamped it closed to ensure no further commodity release during subsequent rail movement. The spillage on GATX 19051's side shell was neutralized and wiped. Spent cleaning materials were placed into an approved 55 gallon drum for appropriate future disposal. No ground impact spillage was observed.

column168: During a BNSF roll-by train inspection, entrained tank car UTLX 205455 was observed leaking commodity from its top fitting area. The BNSF train with entrained UTLX 205455 was stopped at the next available location awaiting BNSF and contract responders arrival to determine and cease the leak source. Responders reported that UTLX 205455's liquid valve was not fully closed and its camlock closure cap was not fully secured, which allowed commodity to escape at the liquid valve's closure. Responder's relieved internal pressure within UTLX 205455 which ended the active leak by 1850 hrs. CDT 9/05/2013. Responder's indicated that the liquid valve's operating handle contacted the interior of the valve housing cover when fully closed which forced the valve's operating handle to move beyond the valve stop and opened the ball valve. Responder's then closed the liquid valve, ensured that the valve's operating handle had sufficient clearance and secured the liquid valve's camlock closure by 1940 hrs. CDT 9/05/2013. Observed ground spillage was treated with a biodegradable compound for hydrocarbon remediation. UTLX 205455 along with six other rail cars that were impacted by commodity spray during train movement were set-out of the train at the next terminal for cleaning which was accomplished on 9/06/2013.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On Saturday September 14, 2013 a KCS employee observed tank car ACFX 200134 leaking from the bottom outlet valve. He notified KCS environmental department and appropriate notifications were made from there and an emergency responder activated to remedy the leaking car.    The responder arrived on site and accessed the tank car. Upon further inspection of the car it was observed that the leak was caused by the top operated bottom outlet valve being leaft in the open position and the bottom outlet cap was not secured fully. Calumet Lubricants Co offered the car into transportation with the tank car appurtenance in the open position with the cap less than tight. The responder tightened the closures appropriately and cleaned up the residual product as necessary.    This incident, if not detected by KCS alert Laredo yard professionals, could have resulted in the release of an entire tank car of Petroleum Lube oil.     * No injuries reported    File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: Recommendations:  The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.     Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121.  The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.  The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: Tank car PPRX 28562 in the railyard was reported emanating a propane type odor. PPRX 28562 was cordoned-off in the railyard. Contract responders inspecting PPRX 28562 reported the odor/vapor source was from its manway closure. A small amount of commodity wetness was also observed around the base of the manway nozzle. All six manway securement bolt nuts were found tool tight. Inspection of the manway gasket condition revealed the applied gasket in the manway cover gasket groove was brittle, cracked and cut; therefore not sealing. A new manway gasket was installed and the manway lid was closed with all securement bolt nuts properly tool tightened. Spillage around the manway nozzle was cleaned. Intact shipper seals 0686689 (manway) and 0686688 (valve housing cover) were replaced by seals numbered 000362 and 000442 respectively.

column168: Initial incident description: It was reported that 1-2 gallons of UN2927 Herbicide was released from a 5-gallon pail onto the trailer floor. Originally, suspected that material contained Hydrofluoric Acid due to incorrect MSDS. Driver was attempting to remove the freight on trailer 313-9608. Upon opening the door the driver noticed a piece of what appeared to be a wood pallet sticking in a 2.5 gallon jug of chemicals.  Supervisor isolated trailer and contacted CWF Safety Department.  Safety Response Coordinator contracted ERTS to coordinate emergency clean up procedures.  ERTS project manager contacted NRC to report release of a RQ based on initial incident description.   Contractor reported that they located one 2.5 gallon pail in the trailer which was punctured by a sharp object. Contractor reported that the entire contents of the pail was released. Contractor reported that most of the freight on the pallet was impacted by the release. Therefore, the contractor removed the pails from the cardboard boxes. The pails had not been impacted but the cardboard boxes had been impacted. The pails were placed onto pallets for continued transit and the boxes are being placed into an overpack. ERTS instructed the contractor to neutralize any free product and the impacted cardboard boxes. Contractor confirmed that the material is contained to the trailer.  Contractor confirmed material release was not an RQ.

On Thursday, September 5th, 2013 at approximately 10:15am, an Air Liquide Orlando, FL Driver arrived at customer Labella Sausage in Brooksville, FL to deliver Liquid Nitrogen using Trailer 48408.    The driver stated that when he arrived at the customer, there were several vehicles near the customer installation area and he proceeded to get out and review the area for hazards so that he could safely back the transport.     After reviewing the hazards and placing his cones, the driver proceeded to re-enter the tractor and back the transport to the cones at the customer installation area. Once he was completed, the driver exited the tractor and proceeded to the back of the trailer to connect the delivery hose to the customer storage vessel. He stated that the pressure in the trailer was 5 psi and he started to cool the trailer's transfer pump and then tried to connect the delivery hose to the customer vessel when he realized he was approximately 6 inches short of the connection. At this time, the driver stated that the only valves that were open on the trailer were the Pump Inlet Valve and the Recert Valve.    After closing the rear trailer doors, the driver proceeded back to the tractor to move the transport. Before he was able to back, the driver had to move the transport approximately 25 feet due to a customer employee that needed to exit in his vehicle.    During the maneuvering of the transport to allow the customer employee to exit the parking area, the driver stated that the trailer valves he had opened prior to this remained open during his maneuvers in the transport (Pump Inlet Valve and the Recert Valve remained open).    Before the driver could complete his maneuvers of the transport to a closer position near the customer installation, he needed the customer to move another vehicle in the way. At approximately 10:25, he parked the transport and went into the customer office which is approximately 10 feet from the customer installation area.     At approximately 10:28, the driver exited the office to go back to the transport and he saw that the rupture disc on the trailer burst and there was product being released at the back of the trailer. The driver stated that the pressure in the trailer at the time of the rupture disc burst was approximately 35 psi and the Pressure Safety Valve (PSV) did not lift prior to the rupture disc bursting.
column169: Instruct all drivers on how the valves should be positioned (open / close) in the trailer when the transport is driven, to include maneuvering at the customer site.       Add precaution to the Air Liquide unloading procedure that instructs all drivers on how the valves should be positioned (open / close) in the trailer when the transport is driven, to include maneuvering at the customer site.      Have Pressure Safety Valve (PSV) involved in incident tested to determine why it did not activate when the pressure increased in the trailer to the set pressure of the PSV before the rupture disc burst.

HMSC WAS NOTIFIED AND IT WAS CONFIRMED THIS WAS A UNDECLARED HAZMAT, REFERENCE # 360429 AND WAS PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP CAGE, NOTHING RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

column168: On September 13, 2013 a liquid Cargo DOT 407 tanker was enroute transporting a load of UN 2582 Haz class 8 PG II Ferric Chloride when it was discovered that the material was reacting with the stainless steel unloading valve resulting in a small but increasing release of material onto the roadway, and soil shoulder. The release resulted in a .5 mile by approximately 15 feet area of the road and adjacent soil to be impacted as well as several storm drains leading to a navigable waterway which were also impacted. Virginia Department of Emergency Management dispatched Petro-Chem. Environmental to manage and oversee the waterway remediation.   There reportedly was two businesses evacuated and closed for approximately 12 hours due to the incident but exact numbers were not made available.   All impacted median was removed and transported off site to be staged pending analytical results. No evidence of impact remained on site. This is a one time incident.
During transit, a cap on a tote failed, allowing product to be released.  Shipper representatives replaced the cap with a serviceable one, wiped off residue, and placed into a container for disposal.

column168: Tank car CITX 221129 in the railyard was reported with commodity wetness on its side shell near the top valve housing area. The local F.D. initially responded and reported CITX 221129's vapor valve was partially open and its closure plug was loose. column168: On September 24, 2013, a 275 gallon tote of UN3266 Sodium Hydroxide experienced a load shift due to improper bracing for transit inside an R&L Carriers tractor-trailer. The incident resulted in the release of an estimated 10 gallons of material to the interior of the trailer and ground below. The material traveled across an asphalt section estimated to be 6" x 100' and into a storm drain. A hole was drilled into the tote that was flipped over on its side and the material was pumped into a new tote. The interior of the trailer was neutralized along with the impacted asphalt. Absorbents were worked in thoroughly and containerized for pending disposal. The Middlesex County Hazmat team neutralized and flushed the impacted drain. All containerized material along with the damaged tote were transported off site for pending disposal.

On September 23, 2013, a 55 gallon drum of UN1170 Ethanol Solutions was crushed due to freight that had been stacked on top of it. The incident resulted in the release of an estimated 4 gallons to the interior of the trailer. The damaged drum was overpacked and the material that had impacted the interior of the trailer evaporated before the contractor had arrived. The overpack was staged onsite to be sent back to the shipper.

Upon inspection, MC Bethge found the B-End liquid line valve to be open  turn and the secondary securement plug to be less than tool tight, the valve was closed and the excess thread tape was removed, the plug was re-installed and the car was secured. column168: Entrained tank car NATX 310295 was reported with a commodity stain on its side shell that appeared to be emanating from NATX 310295's manway closure. column168: One plastic jerrican was found with leakage during breakdown / offload of the pallet / ULD of a freighter flight 01sep.   The staff were evacuated for less than 45 minutes and the Chicago Fire Department ( ORD) was called. The Chicago Fire Department placed the plastic jerrican in a recovery drum, this was marked and later picked up by the consignee.   The drum was later examined and found to have no leaks or holes and the top cap appeared intact .When tipped the drum top did not further leak. Our conclusion was that the drum was overfilled ( shipper error) with not enough room for expansion of the liquid during flight altitude. The liquid leaked out of the top cap , the cap allowed the overfill to leak out , about 1 liter or less.   The shipper and consignee were contacted to see if they could confirm that the drum was overfilled ( for example examining the drum which had leaked )   The consignee ( Givaudan Flavors Corp 100 East 69th Street Cincinnati OHIO 45216 ) was not able to do this since the refused the shipment due to damage . The shipper was also Givaudan - address in report ( Germany)
column169: We gave information to the customs broker ( DHL ) to advise the shipper and consignee ( both Givaudan ) to check these there process so that these shipments were not overfilled in the future as we did not believe there was any damage to the jerrican or any mishandling. The response ( throught the Customs broker DHL  ) was only that they did not want the shipment due to damage .

A driver arrived at the shipper's location to load a shipment of hazardous waste solids into an end dump trailer.  There were heavy rains that morning and the trailer contained some rainwater.  The material was loaded on top of the rainwater and then the now contaminated rainwater leaked out of the rear tailgate.  The spilled material was cleaned up with a suitable absorbant material and placed back into the trailer.  The leak occurred due to a faulty gasket on the trailer which was temporarily sealed for the truck to proceed to the maintenance facility for repairs.
column169: The driver should have dumped out the rainwater prior to loading.  Also, the faulty gasket should have been noticed on the driver's pretrip inspection.  The driver was cautioned to carefully check trailers prior to loading.

column25: OOCL USA Inc. for Afton Chemical
column168: On 9/23/2013, a non-BNSF drayage driver reported to his company's operations that intermodal container OOLU 166758 (destined for export) was leaking an unknown liquid. BNSF was not notified of this possible leaking container (OOLU 166758) until mid-day on 9/24/2013. OOLU 166758 was carefully moved to the facility's transfer dock for lading investigation. Contract responders inspecting the lading within OOLU 166758 reported finding one 55 gallon steel drum (located mid-section of this container on the bottom tier) with a small stress crack in a dented area towards its bottom sidewall. Responders also reported that the leak in the drum was contained by 1340 hrs. PDT, 9/24/2013 after this drum's crack was patched and drum placed into an over-pack drum. The cause of the drum's sidewall crack was suspected to be that the drum was dropped during or prior to container loading. All non-evaporated spillage was cleaned. The over-pack drum containing the compromised drum was earmarked to be returned to the commodity manufacturer.  It should be noted that the drum's labeling indicated that this commodity is not regulated in non-bulk transport in the U.S., but regulated by IMO/IMDG. The hazardous material designation was in the international transport billing received by the BNSF.

The spill was fully captured in the containment area of the loading dock.

column168: On September 26, 2013, a 275 gallon tote of UN1760 Corrosive Liquid, N.O.S. (Organic Acid) experienced an apparent crack in the body of the tote allowing for a release of an estimated 1 cup of material to the body of the tote. On September 27, 2013, a tote transfer was conducted transferring the material into a new tote and the material was sent on to its destination. The damaged tote was transported off site for pending disposal.

On September 30, 2013, a 55 gallon drum of UN1993 Flammable Liquid, N.O.S. was punctured by a forklift drum picker attachment. An estimated 6 ounces was released to the shrink wrap around the drum. No drains or waterways had been impacted by the release. The damaged drum was overpacked and staged on site to be sent back to the shipper.

An aerosol can inside of a box was crushed due to too much weight on top of the box.  R&L Carriers contacted ERTS to oversee environmental operations.  ERTS dispatched SWS to the site to perform remediation activities.

column168: After arrival in the railyard on an inbound BNSF train, tank car GATX 96282 was reported emanating a commodity odor. GATX 96282 was cordoned-off and initial inspection by BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders revealed a small liquid leak at the liquid valve's threaded connection which was apparently not holding a good seal. Responders removed the liquid valve, cleaned the threaded connections, applied new sealant to the threaded areas, re-installed and properly tool tightened the liquid valve. The spillage around the liquid valve connection was wiped and no further indication of commodity leakage was evident. Also noted during GATX 96282's inspection were loose closure plugs on both the liquid and vapor valves; these were tool tightened by the responders.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A BNSF inbound train inspection in the railyard revealed entrained tank car UTLX 205455 with commodity wetness on its side shell. After a detailed inspection of UTLX 205455 by BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders, the responders reported the leak source was at the liquid valve's camlock closure cap. The liquid valve was partially open and its camlock closure cap was not sealing due to worn cam arm locking assemblies. The responders closed the liquid valve and replaced the non-sealing closure cap by installing a new closure cap. Spillage on UTLX 205455's side shell was cleaned and no ground impact from spillage was observed.

column168: LTCX 1609 was found with loud venting and icing on the vent tubes.  The car was inspected and found to have the regulator vavle frozen and venting. column168: On September 18, 2013 at approximately 3:50 PM, A Dana Transportation Service Company truck had started loading Methyl Ethyl Ketone (MEK) when an IMTT Operator discovered that the trailer compartment overflowed.  IMTT Operator immediately stopped loading and contacted his supervisor.  In-house cleanup was conducted resulting from this spill.  An investigation determined that the capacity of this trailer compartment was 1,500 gallons while the order called for 1,450 gallons.  When the accuload meter was approaching 1,450 gallons, the trailer compartment overflowed.  The customer has been notified of this incident and will follow up with transportation company to correct/determine the true capacity of the compartments.

column168: 9/14/13: At approximately 1031AM, conductor of FC09, while performing routine switching in Pavonia Yard, Camden, NJ, noted tank car IAPX 1014, load, Argon Refrigerated Liquid, to be venting/leaking liquid and vapor from the control cabinet on the car's left side.  Ice forming on ground due leaking liquid.  The tank car had arrived at the yard on 9/12/13 on CSXT's Q417 train.    The intact left side cabinet seals "Air Liquide 0499948" and "Air Liquide 0499949" were removed by CR's Risk Mangement Department A. Richter.  Further inspection by CR's A. Richter and emergency response contractor R. Gould, Hepaco-React, noted the liquid valve was not fully closed (required an approximate 1/4 turn for closure), and liquid was leaking past the liquid valve's packing gland.  After securing the valve closed to stop liquid flow, the two nuts on the packing gland required approximately 1-3 full turns to adequately securing the packing gland tool tight.    Car okayed to move to original consignee for unloading at approximately 415pm.  Original shipper of load has been asked to request an OTMA for moving the car from the consignee's facility to a pre-designated shop for inspection of valve, packing gland retainer and packing prior to putting the car back into service.

column168: The driver reported that when he was 1/4 of the way into the transfer of product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank using very low air pressure, he noticed something dripping from the skin of the tank trailer by the landing gear.  He stopped the transfer to put a bucket under the drip and to report the issue.  We weren't sure if maybe rainwater got in the insulation but to play safe, we had the driver complete the unload using a pump to take the pressure off the barrel of the cargo tank.  When the trailer was empty and cleaned, it was brought in to the shop to be checked out.  There was signs of pitting in the steainless steel barrel that may have caused the issue.
column169: Trying to keep a handle on corrosion is an on-going issue.  It would be awesome if all shippers would provide corrosion testing results for their product and a typical stainless steel tank trailer. We try to do our best with our corrosion reference books and online charts but we can't always find the combination of chemicals listed on the MSDS.

column168: PNNL received from Chem-Impex a shipment of four hazardous items, three of the items were identified on the packing list and appeared to packaged and marked appropriately.  The fourth item was an unmarked non-specification fiberboard box with no accompanying documentation identifying it as hazardous.  Within the box was a properly marked/labeled specification bucket.  The package contained 100 grams of triisopropylsilane (UN1993, Flammable liquid, N.O.S., 3, II).  There was no release, injury or disruption of operations.  Inner package was verified by a local shipper and moved on to its final destination.

column25: Great Northern Gathering + Marketing by Great Northern Midstream LLC
column62: Valve Open; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: Entrained tank car VMSX 310422 was reported leaking commodity from its top fitting area onto its side shell. VMSX 310422 was carefully set-out of its train into a nearby spur track. BNSF hazardous material responders inspecting VMSX 310422 reported finding the liquid valve partially open with its closure plug loose with commodity seeping out from the closure plug's orifice. Responders tool tightened the closure plug (4 full turns) which ended any further commodity release and properly closed the liquid valve. A BNSF contractor was notified to clean spillage on the exterior of VMSX 310422 and remediate any observed ground spillage which was accomplished on 9/30/2013.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

On Saturday, September 28th, 2013 at 0251 hours, personnel in the CSXT Russell/Big Four Yard discovered PROX 75177 a loaded tank car of Environmentally Hazardous Substances, Liquid, N.O.S. leaking product from the top of the car. The tank car was isolated and the shipper, Shell Chemicals, Canada LTD. was notified, representative Rick Ferguson, cell 832-712-9770. CHEMTREC report 2013-09-28-00016. Quick Response Contracting, a CSXT emergency response contractor was dispatched to the scene, upon arrival it was determined that a gasket was leaking product between the liquid line valve and the EW dry-lock fitting, upon further investigation the tank car had a pad of nitrogen, and it was determined that the Jamesbury 4 liquid line valve was by-passing product under pressure, the nitrogen pressure was relieved and the release stopped.  On Friday, October 4th, 2013 the product in PROX 75177 was transferred in to TILX 262178, which will be waybilled for disposition.  PROX 75177 was Clean + Purged, and Shell Chemicals will apply for an OTMA-1 for home shop disposition.     An AAR 7.1 form will be filed.  A Special Switch Move was conducted, to place the tank car in a location for transfer.    Cause Code: 300  NARRI: 5x(5+1+0)x(3+0) = 90

On the evening of September 27, 2013 Driver Moore was loading a cargo tanker at the Brace West Well located in Carrollton, Ohio. The driver had loaded approximately 170 barrels of condensate when he heard a loud "pop" noise. The driver directed his attention towards the noise an observed a spark and then an immediate flash fire emanating from a piece of mechanical equipment located in the containment area. The fire traveled through the containment area to a vapor recovery hose that was being used to vent the trailer into the containment area. The fire traveled up the vapor hose to the cargo tanker whereas the trailer began to become engulfed in fire. The driver was unable to shut off the truck or activate the emergency valves on the trailer and was attempting evacuate the area.
column169: ¿ Ensure equipment is properly grounded to approved ground devices  ¿ Ensure that vapor hoses are of sufficient length and routed away from the truck and trailer and downwind from any ignition source.  ¿ Do not load from wells that do not have sealed vapor recovery systems  ¿ Ensure all driver personnel are familiar with well specific procedures and if not familiar, initiate "stop work" authority.

column168: On Monday, September 30, 2013, at approximately 0545 CST, an Air Liquide Industrial Team Driver was driving an empty Liquid Hydrogen transport on I-49 South in Louisiana towards New Orleans to load product into the transport. The driver stated that the inner tire on the driver’s side rear axle blew causing sparks and smoke. The driver immediately proceeded to pull over to the side of the highway when the tire caught fire. Once stopped, the driver quickly got out of the tractor, took his fire extinguisher and went to the back of the trailer to fight the fire. He was able to initially extinguish the fire, however it started again and he proceeded to call 911 to report the incident.     Because of the heat, the pressure rose inside the Liquid Hydrogen Trailer and the Pressure Safety Valve (PSV) lifted releasing Hydrogen gas out of the vent stack into the atmosphere. The escaping Hydrogen gas ignited, causing a vent stack fire on the trailer. Louisiana Emergency Responders were able to extinguish the Vent Stack fire by using the trailers Helium Fire Abatement System, and the pressure inside the trailer decreased to below the PSV limit, however the PSV did not reseat causing Hydrogen gas to continue to slowly escape out of the vent stack. In order to get the pressure to a safe level, an Air Liquide employee was able to safely conduct a controlled venting of the trailer and brought the pressure down from approximately 170 psi to 3-5 psi.    Both North and South bound lanes of I-49 near Alexandria, LA (mile marker 63) were closed during the incident  - the controlled venting was completed at 1125 CST and the trailer was moved off of the interstate at 1405 CST.    Northbound traffic resumed at 1230 CST and Southbound resumed at 1410 CST.
column169: Re-training on proper pre-trip inspections will be conducted, as well as ensuring that the required preventative maintenance is done on the transports at least once a month.

column168: ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT JOB #34439    ON SEPTEMBER 18, 2013, CON-WAY TRUCKOAD, INC (CON-WAY) PERSONNEL CONTACTED MR. DAVID HOOPER WITH ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT AT APPROXIMATELY 1645 CST AND INFORMED HIM THAT TRUCK OWNED BY CON-WAY HAD OVERTURNED AT THE INTERSECTION OF LAKEFRONT LANE AND STATE HWY U IN ST. JOSEPH, MO. CON-WAY PERSONNEL STATED THAT IT WAS BELIEVED THAT THE DRIVER WAS DRIVING TOO FAST, AND FAILED TO SLOW TO AND APPROPRIATE SPEED FOR THE TRUCK TO MAKE THE TURN, RESULTING IN THE TRUCK AND TRAILER OVERTURNING. DUE THE RATE OF SPEED ANS SEVERITY OF IMPACT, IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY 500 BATTERIES WERE DAMAGED, RELEASING SULFURIC ACID INSIDE THE TRAILER AND ONTO THE SOIL.    MR. HOOPER INITIATED AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE ON BEHALF OF CON-WAY, MOBILIZING A RESPONSE TEAM OUT OF KANSAS CITY, MO TO RESPOND TO THE INCIDENT. UPON ARRIVAL, THE RESPONSE TEAM NOTED THAT THE TRUCK WAS COMPLETELY UPSIDE DOWN AND THE TRAILER DESTROYED, WITH BATTERIES STRUNG OUT FOR APPROXIMATELY 60-70 YARDS. RESPONSE PERSONNEL ALSO NOTED THAT ELECTRIC LINES WERE DOWN, AND HAD TO WAIT UNTIL THE ELECTRIC COMPANY ARRIVED ON SITE TO REMOVE THE LINES FROM THE AREA. ONCE THE LINES WERE REMOVED, RESPONSE PERSONNEL BEGAN RECOVERING THE BATTERIES, PLACING THEM IN 30-CY ROLLOFF BOXES WHICH WERE DELIVERED TO THE SITE EARLIER. EMERGENCY LINE LOCATES WERE CALLED IN, AS VARIOUS AREAS OF SOIL HAD BEEN IMPACTED WITH SULFURIC ACID FROM THE DAMAGED BATTERIES. BATTERY RECOVERY FROM THE ACCIDENT CONTINUED THROUGH THE NIGHT, WITH ALL BATTERIES BEING RECOVERED AND SECURED IN THE ROLLOFF BOXES. THE FOLLOWING MORNING, RESPONSE PERSONNEL UTILIZED A SKID STEER AND BACKHOE TO REMOVE THE CONTAMINATED SOIL, PLACING IN A ROLLOFF BOX FOR DISPOSAL AT A LATER DATE.    THE DAMAGE TO THE BATTERIES INCLUDED THE BATTERY CASES SPLITTING OR BEING CRACKED AS A RESULT OF THE ACCIDENT. THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETE ON SEPTEMBER 19, 2013. RECYCLING OF THE BATTERIES IS CURRENTLY ON-GOING.

THIS UNLABELED AND UNMARKED SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING DURING THE SORTING OPERATION. AT LEAST 4 EMPLOYEES WERE EXPOSED TO THIS SHIPMENT AND APPROXIMATELY 20 OTHER PACKAGES WERE AFFECTED BY THE SPILL. UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER METAL CAN THAT WAS LEAKING FROM THE CLOSURE, IT WAS SUSPECTED AS POSSIBLY BEING UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS AS THE INNER PACKAGING HAD A CORROSIVE AND TOXIC LABEL ON THE INNER CAN. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED ON SATURDAY SEPTEMBER 14, 2013 BUT I COULD ONLY LEAVE A VOICEMAIL MESSAGE. I ASLO TRIED TO CONTACT CHERICE MCDANIEL OF THE IND/FAA ON SATURDAY SEPTEMBER 14, 2013 AT 15:05 (CDT) TO INFORM HER OF THE INCIDENT. I THEN EMAILED HER MY NOTIFICATION FORM & PACKAGE SCANS SHOWING HOW THE SHIPMENT HAD MOVED. ON MONDAY, SEPTEMBER 16,2013 I SPOKE TO A PARTY IN THE SHIPPING OFFICE OF THIS COMPANY. HE PROVIDED MSDS FOR THE PRODUCTS. I THE EMAILED THAT TO CHERICE MCDANIEL OF THE IND/FAA. I LATER FOUND OUT THAT CHERICE HAD NOT SEEN THE SHIPMENT ON MONDAY, BUT OTHER FAA AGENTS DUNLAP OF THE FAA FEDEX FACILITY AND HAD SEEN IT. I WAS THEN TOLD CONTACT SOPHIA DUNLAP OF THE FAA  WAS WORKING THIS INCIDENT, SO EVERYTHING WAS EMAILED TO HER SO SHE COULD DO THE INVESTIGATION. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD AND WAS LATER RELEASED BY THE FAA AND WE WERE WORKING WITH THE SHIPPER ON GETTING THE PACKAGE PREPARED FOR MOVEMENT VIA TRUCK.

column168: OUR TANKER CAME OVER THE HILL ON SYCAMORE VIEW ROAD AT 45 MPH AS ITS WEIGHT, THE BANK AND THE SLOPE OF THE ROAD PULLED HIM ON TO THE OUTSIDE CURB. ONE TIRE WENT ON TOP OF THE CURB, AS THE FRONT BUMPER HIT THE MAILBOX OF STEVE BAIEL. OUR DRIVER THEN TRIED TO PULL BACK ONTO THE ROAD AS HE SAW AN ELECTRIC POLE AND BOX IN FRONT OF HIM.  AS HE GOT BACK ONTO THE ROAD AND DROPPED OFF THE CURB, THE TANKER LAID ONTO ITS PASSENGER SIDE SKIDDING TO A STOP ON THE ASPHALT ROAD. TWO 6 INCH RIPS IN THE BARREL WALL AT THE BAFFLES BEGAN TO LEAK FROM THE UNDER SIDE IF THE TANKER.  NOW KNOWING HOW BIG THE LEAK WAS, WE DID NOT RAISE THE TANKER UNTIL WE SENT FOR 2 VAC TRUCKS AND ANOTHER TANKER TO PUMP OFF THE REMAINING FUEL. AFTER STICKING THE PUMPED OFF FUEL, WE DELIVERED THE REMAINING 1831 GALLONS TO KROGER #405 IN BARTLETT, TN. FIRE DEPARTMENTS FOR MEMPHIS AND BARTLETT USED DIRT AND PLASTIC TO COVER DRAINS. BOOMS WERE PLACED AT EACH END OF THE STORM DRAIN TO STOP THE SPREAD OF FUEL TO THE STILL WATER ON THE OTHER SIDE OF THE STREET. LEVEES WERE FORMED OUT OF DIRT AS THE FUEL WENT DOWN HILL TO THE DRAIN. A SERIRES OF ABSORBENT BOOMS WERE INSTALLED ALONG A DRAINAGE DITCH WHERE WATER IS ROUTED AWAY FROM THE SPILL AFFECTED STORM DRAINS. THE STORM DRAINS WERE FLUSHED UNDER THE GUIDANCE OF THE USEPA AND TEDC AND EFFLUENT WATER COLLECTED AND DISPOSED OF. THE CREEK IS BEING MONITORED AFTER RAIN EVENTS IN ACCORDANCE WITH A PLAN APPROVED BY THE TEDEC. SOIL CONTAMINATED BY THE SPILL, SITUATED BETWEEN THE CURB AND SIDEWALK WAS ALSO EXCAVATED AND DISPOSED OF OFF SITE. CONFORMATION SOIL SMAPLES WERE COLLECTED FROM THE BASE OF THE SIEDWALK AREA EXCAVATION AND THESE ARE BEING FORWARDED IN A REPORT TO THE TDEC. THE EXCAVATION AREA WAS TREATED WITH MICROBLAZE AND SUBSEQUENTLY BACKFILLED AND RESTORED. DAMAGE TO PROPERTY AND THE ROADWAY IS BEING RESTORED AT THIS TIME AND SHOULD ALL BE COMPLETED BY EARLY NOVEMBER 2013.
column169: EVEN AT A 45 MPH SPEED, GOING DOWN HILL IN A CURVE BANKED TO THE DIRECTION OF INERTIA, PULLS ON A HIGH CENTER OF GRAVITY VEHICLE. PEOPLE LIVING ON THAT CURVE STATED NUMEROUS ACCIDENTS OF THEIR OWN AND BY OTHERS DUE TO THE SLOPE AND WRONG BANK OF THE CURVE. ONCE OUR DRIVER GOT HIS TIRE ON THE OUTSIDE CURB, PULLING BACK ONTO THE ROAD, CAUSED THE ROLL OVER. SPEED IS THE ONLY ELEMENT OF THIS ACCIDENT WE COULD CONTROL.

column168: On September 13, 2013, R&L Carriers experienced a release of approximately 50 pounds of UN3378 Sodium Carbonate Peroxyhydrate from five 50 pound bags. The release impacted the trailer floor, and was due to the bags ripping on a skid during a load shift while in transit. The release was immediate, and considered a one-time event. Upon discovery of the release at 1130 EST, R&L Carriers called ERTS to oversee environmental operations, and restricted personnel from entering the impacted area. An environmental response team was dispatched within a half hour to clean up the impacted area.

column168: While driver was enroute to delivery site, he stopped approx. 1 mile from the destination in an open lot across from convenient store where he asked for directions. Upon returning to his unit, he noticed material escaping out of the back of trailer onto the pavement. He placed bucket and absorbent pads under trailer to prevent any further material from hitting the ground. Upon opening trailer doors, it was discovered that the load had shifted from apparent previous hard break which resulted in a nail from pallet puncturing a hole in plastic tote. Emergency Response Team, OP-TECH was contracted to respond. Material in damaged tote was transferred into another UN Spec tote container. All contaminated material and clean-up debris was placed in two separate drums and taken off-site by OP-TECH for proper disposal. NOTE; Pan on spill/end gate was found to have small pinholes which resulted in material not being contained within the trailer.
column169: 1) HAZMAT'S TERMINAL MANAGER DISCUSSED WITH THE SHIPPER, THE PROPER METHOD IN LOADING TOTES.  2) HAZMAT'S MAINTENANCE DEPT. WILL BEGIN WATER TESTING PANS ON SPILL/END GATES ON BOX VAN TRAILERS IN THE FLEET. NOTE: ALL VANS ARE EQUIPPED WITH AN 8" STILL PAN, FULL LENGTH OF TRAILER. THE GATE ON END IS PLACED IN DOWN POSITION WHEN TRAILERS ARE LOADED TO PREVENT ANY POTENTIAL RELEASE.  3) FLEET MESSAGE WAS SENT TO ALL DRIVERS TO CALL COMPLIANCE OR OPERATIONS DEPT. WHEN THEY ARE PICKING UP TOTES OR ODD SIZE ;CONTAINERS SO PROPER SECUREMENT MEASURES CAN BE REVIEWED AND APPROVED.

column168: THE CON-WAY DRIVER DISCOVERD A MATERIAL LEAKING FROM THE CENTER OF THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CALLED THE CON-WAY DEPARTMENT AND REPORTED THE INCIDENT. THE CON-WAY SAFETY DEPARTMENT CALLED THEIR EMERGENCY REPONSE CONTRACTOR, ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT AND A LOCAL EMERGENCY REPONSE TEAM (TEAM) WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE. THE TEAM DONNED PROPER PPE AND MADE ENTRY INTO THE TRAILER.    WHEN THE TRAILER WAS ORIGINALLY LOADED, A "FIRST" GROUP OF DRUMS WAS PLACED INTO THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER AND A "FIRST" LOAD STRAP WAS PLACED ACROSS THE TRAILER TO SECURE THE FIRST GROUP. A SPACE OF SEVERAL FEET WAS LEFT BETWEEN THE FIRST GROUP OF DRUMS AND A SECOND GROUP OF DRUMS. A SECOND LOAD STRAP WAS PLACED ACROSS THE TRAILER TO PREVENT THE SECOND GROUP OF DRUMS IN THE FIRST GROUP, CAUSING BENDING IN THE SIDES OF TWO DRUMS.    DURING TRANSPORTATION THE SECOND LOAD STRAP OF DISENGAGED FOR UNKNOWN REASONS AND THE SECOND OF DRUMS FELL FORWARD INTO THE FIRST GROUP OF DRUMS. THE TOP EDGE OF DRUMS FROM THE SECOND GROUP, IMPACTED THE SIDES OF THE DRUMS IN THE FIRST GROUP, CAUSING BENDING IN THE SIDES OF TWO DRUMS.    A CUT APPROXIMATELY 1/4 INCH LONG IN THE SIDES OF TWO DRUMS IN THE FIRST GROUP RESULTED AND HAD CAUSED THE LEAKAGE. THE DRUMS RELEASED APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS EACH UNTIL AN INTERNAL VACUUM WAS CREATED, STOPPING THE LEAKAGE.    THE DAMAGE DRUMS WERE OVER PACKED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS.

column168: AT APPRROXIMATELY 10 PM A MCILVAINE TRUCK DRIVER CAME IN THE PLANT AND PROCEEDED TO AMMONIA STORAGE TO RETRIEVE THE #030 TRAILER, WHICH HAD BEEN LOADED FOR HIM ON THE 2-10 SHIFT. AFTER FILLING OUT HIS PAPER WORK AT THE AMMONIA STORAGE LOADING OFFICE HE PROCEEDED TO CONNECT UP HIS TRACTOR TO HIS TRAILER. THE DRIVER SAID AT NO TIME DURING THIS DID HE SEE OR SMELL ANYTHING LEAKING FROM HIS TRAILER. AFTER THE TRAILER WAS CONNECTED HE PROCEEDED NORTH TOWARD THE SCALE, THEN HE APPLIED HIS TRAILER TO BRAKE TO MAKE SURE HE WAS CONNECTED. AT THIS TIME, HE HEARD A POP AND STOPPED TO INVESTIGATE. WHEN HE SAW THE LEAK ON TOP OF HIS TRAILER, THE DRIVER BACKED THE TRAILER TO THE LOADING DOCK AND NOTIFIED #5 CONTROL ROOM. OPERATIONS THEN OFF LOADED THE LIQUID IN THE AMMONIA TRAILER BACK TO A EMPTY RAILCAR AND THEN FLARED OFF THE VAPOR PRESSURE TO THE STACK. IT WAS LATER FOUND THAT THE LEAK WAS A FAILED RELIEF VALVE. ONCE THE TRAILER WAS SAFE, IT WAS RELEASED TO THE MCLLVAINE SHOP.
column169: VALVE BEING REPLACED WITH NEW VALVE.    VALVE THAT FAILED WAS SENT TO EMERSON VALVE INC FOR THIRD PARTY TESTING AND ANALYSIS.

column168: ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT JOB #34439 ON SEPTEMBER 18, 2013, CON-WAY TRUCKLOAD, INC. (CON-WAY) PERSONNEL CONTACTED MR. DAVID HOOPER WITH ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT AT APPROXIMATELY 1645 CST AND INFORMED HIM THAT A TRUCK OWNED BY CON-WAY HAD OVERTURNED AT THE INTERSECTION OF LAKEFRONT LANE AND STATE HWY U IN ST. JOSEPH, MO. CON-WAY PERSONNEL STATED THAT IT WAS BELIEVED THAT THE DRIVER WAS DRIVING TOO FAST, AND FAILED TO SLOW TO AN APPROPRIATE SPEED FOR THE TRUCK TO MAKE THE TURN, RESULTING IN THE TRUCK AND TRAILER OVERTURNING. DUE TO THE RATE OF SPEED AND SEVERITY OF IMPACT, IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY 500 BATTERIES WERE DAMAGED, RELEASING SULFURIC ACID INSIDE THE TRAILER AND ONTO THE SOIL. MR. HOOPER INITIATED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE ON BEHALF OF CON-WAY, MOBILIZING A RESPONSE TEAM OUT OF KANSAS CITY, MO TO RESPOND TO THE INCIDENT. UPON ARRIVAL, THE RESPONSE TEAM NOTED THAT THE TRUCK WAS COMPLETELY UPSIDE DOWN AND THE TRAILER DESTROYED, WITH BATTERIES STRUNG OUT FOR APPROXIMATELY 60-75 YARDS. RESPONSE PERSONNEL ALSO NOTED THAT ELECTRIC LINES WERE DOWN, AND HAD TO WAIT UNTIL THE ELECTRIC COMPANY ARRIVED ON SITE TO REMOVE THE LINES FROM THE AREA. ONCE THE LINES WERE REMOVED, RESPONSE PERSONNEL BEGAN RECOVERING THE BATTERIES, PLACING THEM IN 30-CY ROLLOFF BOXES WHICH WERE DELIVERED TO THE SITE EARLIER. EMERGENCY LINES LOCATED WERE CALLED IN, AS VARIOUS AREAS OF SOIL HAD BEEN IMPACTED WITH SULFURIC ACID FROM THE DAMAGED BATTERIES. BATTERY RECOVERY FROM THE ACCIDENT CONTINUED THROUGH THE NIGHT, WITH ALL BATTERIES BEING RECOVERED AND SECURED IN THE ROLLOFF BOXES. THE FOLLOWING MORNING, RESPONSE PERSONNEL UTILIZED A SKID STEER AND BACKHOE TO REMOVE THE CONTAMINATED SOIL, PLACING IN A ROLLOFF BOX FOR DISPOSAL AT A LATER DATE. THE DAMAGE TO THE BATTERIES INCLUDED THE BATTERY CASES SPLITTING OR BEING CRACKED AS A RESULT OF THE ACCIDENT. THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETE ON SEPTEMBER 19, 2013. RECYCLING OF THE BATTERIES IS CURRENTLY ON-GOING.

EMI JOB#34434: ON MONDAY, 09-16-13, A CON-WAY TRUCKLOAD, INC. (CTI) DRIVER (MR. RAUL VENEGAS) WAS OPERATING A TRACTOR-TRAILER #24125). THE UNIT WAS TRAVELING EASTBOUND ON INTERSTATE HIGHWAY 80 NEAR MINERAL, IL. MR. VENEGAS PULLED THE UNIT OFF THE ROADWAY AND PARKED ON THE SOUTHSIDE OF THE FOG LINE ON THE SHOULDER OF THE ROADWAY AT MILE MARKER 38. AS THE UNIT WAS PARKED, ANOTHER VEHICLE (TRACTOR-TRAILOR UNIT) STRUCK THE REAR LEFT SIDE OF THE CTI TRAILER UNIT. THE CTI TRAILER UNIT WAS TRANSPORTING VARIOUS FREIGHT ITEMS TO INCLUDE 55-GALLON POLY DRUMS OF EXTRACT FLAVORING (FLAMMABLE LIQUID) AND 5-GALLON METAL PAILS OF CORROSIVE LIQUID (CONTAINING AMINES). AS A RESULT OF THE IMPACT, ONE (1) 55 GALLON DRUM OF THE EXTRAXT FLAVORING WAS COMPROMISED AND FIVE (5) OF THE 5 GALLON PAILS OF THE CORROSIVE PRODUCT WERE ALSO COMPROMISED. THE ISP CLOSED THE EASTBOUND LANES TO THROUGH TRAFFIC. AT APPROXIMATELY 1813 HOURS (CTZ) MR. TIRSO BELTRAN OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT, INC. (EMI) RECEIVED A CALL FROM MS. MARY BERG OF CTI.

column168: THIS REPORT IS ALSO RELATED TO AN INCIDNET REPORT ASSOCIATED WITH THE UPS PACKAGE ASSIGNED TO TRACKING NUMBER 1Z7509830303580099. AT 18:08 HRS, EMPLOYEES IN THE UPS MESQUIE HUB REPORTED A FIRE ON A CONVEYOR BELT INVOLVED PACKAGES BEING MOVED TO AN OUTBOUND DOOR. THE FACILITY IMMEDIATELY EVACUATED THE UPS MECHANICS USED FIRE EXTINGUISHERS TO PUT OUT THE FIRE.  DEBRIS INCLUDED TWO 1-GALLON CANS OF RESISTOL FELT HAT STIFFENER.  DESPITE THE PRESENCE OF CLIPS ON THE CAN LIDS, ONE CAN WAS EMPTY AND THE OTHER CONTAINED ABOUT 1/3 OF A GALLON.  PRODUCT LABELING ON THE CANS WARNED OF FLAMMABLE VAPORS AND SUBSEQUENT RESEARCH PRODUCED AN MSDS THAT IDENTIFIED THE PRODUCT AS UN1263 AND ASSOCIATED THESE CANS WITH THE TRACKING NUMBERS GIVEN.  THE OUTER PACKAGING FOR THESE CANS WAS DESTROYED IN THE FIRE, MAKING IT IMPOSSIBLE TO IDENTIFY THE DETAILS OF THE SHIPMENT, ALTHOUGH REPORTEDLY THEY WERE OFFERED AS LTD QTY SHIPMENTS.  THE FACILITY WAS RE-OCCUPIED IN SLIGHTLY OVER 30 MINUTES AND WORK RESTARTED WHERE POSSIBLE.  AFTER CLEANING THE DEBRIS FOR DISPOSAL, IN ACCORDANCE WITH ENVIRONMENTAL REGULATIONS.  UPS ENGINEERING STAFF REPAIRED THE CONVEYOR BELT.  THE FACILITY RESUMED FULL OPERATION WITHIN TWO HOURS.  ALL INFORMATION IN PART IV, CONSEQUENCES RESPRESENTS THE TOTAL RESULTS OF THE EVENTS INVOLVING THIS PACKAGE AND 1Z7509830303580099.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 12:00 PM ON THURSDAY SEPTEMBER 12, 2013 OUR TRACTOR TRAILER CONTAINING 8000 GALLONS OF HEATING OIL ROLLED OVER AT THE SOUTH END OF THE ROTARY CIRCLE ON ROUTE 9 IN KINDERHOOK, NY. THE ROLLOVER CAUSED THE TANK TO RUPTURE ON THE PASSENGER SIDE OF THE TANK CAUSING A RELEASE. THE FUEL MIGRATED AND FLOWED SOUTH TOWARDS THE GUTTERS ALONG THE ROADWAY WITH SOME ENTERING CATCH BASINS. THERE ARE TWO PONDS IN THE AREA THAT ALSO RECEIVED SOME OF THE HEATING OIL. JERRY SALVO, LONG OIL HEAT, INC SUPERVISOR, UPON NOTIFICATION CALLED ALBANY TANK SERVICE TO ADMINISTER CLEAN UP AND SUNNYSIDE GARAGE TO UPRIGHT THE TRACTOR TRAILER AND TOW BACK TO THEIR YARD. TOWN OF KINDERHOOK HIGHWAY RESPONDED WITH MULTIPLE LOADS OF SAND TO BUILD BERMS ALONG THE ROADWAY. NYS DEC CONTACTED CLEAN HARBORS TO HELP CONTAIN AND CLEAN UP THE OIL. APPROXIMATELY 6000 GALLONS WERE ABLE TO CONTAINED AND RECOVERED BY ALBANY TANK AND CLEAN HARBORS. NYS DOT RESPONDED AND DIRECTED ROADWAY CLEAN UP AND OPERATIONS WHILE ATTEMPTING TO ASSESS ROAD CONDITIONS. PLEASE SEE ATTACHED DOCUMENTS FOR MORE INFORMATION.
column169: WE HAVE ADDED ADDITIONAL TRAINING WHICH INCLUDES EXTRA CAUTION WHEN DRIVING THROUGH ROUNDABOUTS, ROLLOVER PREVENTION AND A POLICY THAT REQUIRES DRIVERS TO ENTER ALL ROUNDABOUTS AT LESS THAN 5 MPH IF STOPPING IS NOT NECESSARY.

column168: ON 9-19-13 PACIFIC TANK LINES, INC DRIVER WAS MAKING A GASOLINE DELIVERY TO TESORO SITE #68735 LOCATED AT 601 E HOLT BLVD. ONTARIO CA. 91761. OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE SITE AT APPROXIMATELY 12:50  AND SPOTTED HIS VEHICLE FOR THE DELIVERY. OUR DRIVER BEGAN TO OFF LOAD THE TRUCK WHICH WAS A 4000 GALLON COMPARTMENT, OUR DRIVER THEN TRIED TO HOOK UP HIS SECOND SET OF DELIVERY HOSES BUT THEY WOULD NOT REACH. OUR DRIVER THEN ENTERED THE TRUCK AND MOVED THE VEHICLE WHILE THE HOSES WERE ATTACHED TO THE VEHICLE AND PRODUCT WAS UNLOADING/FLOWING. WHEN THE DRIVER MOVED THE VEHICLE IT CAUSED THE PRODUCT HOSE TO TEAR CAUSING A RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 150 GALLONS OF GASOLINE. THE SPILL LASTED FOR APPROXIMATELY SEVEN TO TEN SECONDS. WHEN OUR DRIVER REALIZED THE MISTAKE HE EXITED THE CAB OF THE VEHICLE AND IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE DUMP VALVE OF THE VEHICLE STOPPING THE FLOW OF PRODUCT. OUR DRIVER THEN RETRIEVED THE VEHICLES EMERGENCY SPILL KIT AND BEGAN TO DIKE OFF THE AREA. THE SITES MANAGER CALLED 911 TO HAVE THE ONTARIO FIRE DEPARTMENT DISPATACHD TO THE SITE, HE THEN BROUGHT OUT KITTY LITTER TO HELP CONTAIN THE SPILL. PACIFIC TANK LINES, INC DISPATCH OFFICE WAS CONTACTED BY THE DRIVER AT APPROXIMATELY 13:05 AND PTL MANAGMENT WAS DISPATACHED TO THE SITE. AT 13:09 PACIFIC TANK LINES, INC. SAFETY MANAGER CONTACTED THE COMPANIES CONTRACTED ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN-UP COMPANY TO DISPATCH EQUIPMENT TO THE SITE FOR CLEAN-UP. AT 13:25 PACIFIC TANK LINES, INC. ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY ARRIVED ON SCENE AND BEGAN STAGING THE EQUIPMENT FOR CLEAN-UP. ANOTHER ASSESSMENT OF THE SITE WAS PERFORMED AND ONTARIO FIRE LEFT THE SITE. AT 15:05 CLEAN-UP OPERATIONS BEGAN, ALL STANDING PRODUCT WAS VACCUMED UP AND ALL ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED AND DRUMMED. THE SITE WAS THEN POWER-WASHED AND CLEANED. AT 15:30 THE RESPONSE WAS TERMINATED.
column169: ALL PACIFIC TANK LINES, INC. DRIVERS HAVE BEEN RE-TRAINED ON THE DANGERS OF MOVING A VEHICLE WHILE DURING OFFLOADING OPERATIONS. ALL DRIVERS HAVE BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED ON COMPANY REQUIRED OFF-LOADING PROCEDURES.

column168: ON THE MORNING OF 9/27/13 A DIESEL FUEL TANKER TRUCK OPERATED BY AG PUS DELIVERED FUEL TO THE AFG STORAGE FACILITY LOCATED @ 2202 DOYLE RD IN NEW HAVEN, IN. THE TANKER TRUCK BEGAN OFF LOADING INTO ONE 10,000 GAL ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK (AST) LOCATED INSIDE AN ENCLOSED NEAR TO BUILDING. THERE WAS AN UNKNOWN AMOUNT OF FUEL INSIDE THE AST PRIOR TO FILLING THE TANK. THE TANKER TRUCK OPERATOR UNLOAD HIS FULL LOAD INTO THE AST, WHICH COULD NOT HOLD THE FULL LOAD. THEREFORE THE FUEL WAS FORCED OUT THE TANK'S VENT PIPE. AS A RESULT APPROXIMATELY 2000 GAL OF RED DIESEL FUEL WAS SPILLED INSIDE THE AST SECONDARY CONTAINMENT. APPROXIMATELY 500 GAL. ESCAPED THE CONTAINMENT & IMPACTED THE GROUND SURFACE. SOME OF THE SPILLED DIESEL FUEL FLOWED OUT OF THE DIESEL TANK BUILDING & ENTERED A STORM DRAIN CATCH BASIN. APPROXIMATELY 50 GAL. OF DIESEL FUEL WAS DISCHARGED FROM THE STORM DRAIN INTO MARTIN DITCH LOCATED SOUTH OF FACILITY. ITEM ASSIGNED INCIDENT *40429 TO SPILL.
column169: THE TANKER TRUCK OPERATOR WAS LET GO. NEW DRIVER HIRED & TRAINED.

column168: DRIVER FAILED TO MAINTAIN LANE AND DROVE INTO MEDIAN OVERTURNING TRUCK & TRAILER. ONE 10 GALLON TOTE WAS DAMAGED AND RELEASED APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS, WHICH WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP.

column168: A.P GRIFFIN UNITS WERE TRAVELLING WESTERN US HWY 84. UNITS REVERSED LEFT OFF OF ROADWAY INTO MEDIUM. THE DRIVER OVERTURNED TO THE RIGHT. UNITS CROSSED  BENT OVER THE LEFT AND BROUGHT TRUCK TRADER INTO RIGHT SHOULDER OF HWY DRIVER OVERTURNED TO THE RIGHT. THIS CAUSED TRUCK UNITS TO ROLL ON ITS RIGHT SIDE AND CONTINUE TO ROLL 1 REVOLUTION AND COME TO REST WITH TRACTOR UPRIGHT AND TRAILER LYING ON LEFT SIDE.DRIVER WAS EJECTED FROM TRACTOR RESULTING IN FATALITY. TX DPS WAS CONTACTED BY A LOCAL FARMER DPS CONTACTED TX CCT WHO ARRIVED ON SCENE AND MADE EARTH DUM TO CERTAIN TO CONTAIN DESIEL FUEL. R.P GRIFFIN TRUCK SERVICE CONTACTED CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES OF PLANO TX. FOR RESPONSE AND MITIGATION. IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT DIESEL FUEL WAS LEAKING  FROM THE DRUM LIDS OF COMPARTMENTS #3 & #4 PRESSURE FROM THE IMPACT HAD CAUSED FAILURE OF THE DOME LID SCALE LEAKAGE WAS SLOW RESULTING IN THE LOSS OF 535 GALLONS. HWY 84 WAS BLOCKED IN BOTH DIRECTIONS UNTIL THE TRAILER COULD BE SAFELY TURNED UPRIGHT AND REMAINING DISEL FUEL REMOVED FROM TRAILER AND WRECKAGE REMOVED FROM THE SCENE BY LUBBOCK WEATHER SERVICE. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN A SMALL AREA AROUND TRAILER. CURA COMPLETED ALL MITIGATION ON 10/30/13 INCIDENT WAS REVISED BY CARLTON ON 10/30/13.

column168: OUR CTI DRIVER WAS LOADED WITH COPPER CONCENTRATE AT MINERAL PARK IN GOLDEN VALLEY, AZ. WHEN MATERIAL WAS LOADED INTO HIS BELLY DUMP TRAILER BY LOADER, THERE WAS A HOT SPOT IN THE MATERIAL. DRIVER PROCEEDED TO LAVEEN AZ, AND MATERIAL STARTED TO SMOKE IN THE AREA OF MORRISTOWN, AZ ON HWY 60. DRIVER PULLED OFF, CALLED FIRE DEPARTMENT, ALONG WITH POLICE A SECTION OF WHY 60 WAS SHUT DOWN FOR THREE HOURS. THE AREA SMOLDERING IN THE TRAILER WAS PUT OUT WITH WATER BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT. AT NO TIME WAS THERE A FIRE. AFTER DETERMINING THERE WAS NO MORE SMOKE, TRUCK WAS ALLOWED TO PROCEED TO CTI YARD IN LAVEEN, AZ.
column169: TO ENSURE IT DOES NOT HAPPEN AGAIN, MINERAL PARK NOW SPREADS MATERIAL OUT TO MAKE SURE THERE ARE NOT HOT SPOTS  AFTER THAT DETERMINATION PRODUCT IS LOADED. CTI DRIVERS ALSO NOW CARRY A THERMAL GUN TO CHECK LOAD TEMPERATURE BEFORE LEAVING.

column168: CPS WAS ATTEMPTING TO UNLOAD A RAILCAR OWNED BY CHEVRON. DURING THE UNLOADING OPERATION, CPS ATTEMPTED TO CLOSE THE MAIN RAILCAR VALVE MECHANISM. THE VALVE FAILED TO CLOSE HOWEVER, THERE WAS NO OUTWARD SIGN OF THE FAILURE. THE RAILCAR VALVE, WHICH WAS STUCK IN THE OPEN POSITION, CAUSED THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE RAILCAR TO BE RELEASED. THE CPS LOCATION EMPLOYEE RESPONDERS ASSUMED A DEFENSIVE POSITION WITH THE PRODUCT. USING CEMENT BLOCKS AND CHANNELING THE PRODUCT TO A RINSE PAD, AND THE INTO SECONDARY CONTAINMENT, THEY WERE ABLE TO RECOVER ABOUT 25% OF THE PRODUCT. THEY USED DIRT, BROUGHT IT FROM OFF SITE, TO SOAK UP THE BALANCE. IT WAS THEN TAKEN TO A LOCAL GROWER'S FIELD FOR AGRONOMIC FIELD APPLICATION WITH THE APPROVAL OF THE ON SCENE WASHINGTON STATE DEPARTMENT OF ECOLOGY REPRESENTATIVE. IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS OR NEED ADDITIONAL INFORMATION PLEASE CONTACT THE UNDERSIGNED.
column169: THE INCIDENT PRECIPATATED DUE TO DEFECTIVE RAILCAR EQUIPMENT. WE COMMUNICATED WITH THE RAILCAR OWNER, CHEVRON REGARDING THE EVENT AND THE HAVE HAD THE CAR TRANSPORTED TO THEIR MAINTENANCE SHOP.

column62: Fire, Temperature, or Heat; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: ;Flight 1159 was a scheduled 19:25 departure from ORD. At 19:45 while on climbout from ORD to STL. Flight Attendants in the aft end of the aircraft began to smell a strong electrical burning odor and reported it to the cockpit.Flight 1159 declared an emergency and air interrupted back to ORD. Flight Attendants began querying customers inthe area of the smell about electronic devices and then began checking overhead binds. A smoldering briefcase was noted almost immediately in the overhead bin above row 26A&B. The Flight Attendants began fighting the fire with Halon fire extinguishers and put the fire out. They removed the briefcase to an empty serving cart from the galley and covered the briefcase with ice. Upon landing, the aircraft was stopped on the runway and met by ORD Crash,Fire, Rescue. They removed the bag from the aircraft. The aircraft then taxied to the gate and customers weredeplaned. The aircraft was N493, an MD80 and upon maintenance inspection no damage was found to the overhead bin.What was found in the briefcase that caused the fire was a spare lithium ion battery for a Nikon camera. The battery was 7.4V 12Wh. It was placed, by the passenger, in an outer pocket of the briefcase. In the outer pocket was alan yard of the type used for IDs to hang around a person's neck. The metal parts of the lanyard came into contact with the anode and cathode of the battery causing a short and driving the battery into thermal runaway.•
column169: This continues to be a public education issue where more needs to be done to educate the travelling public on thedangers of lithium batteries and the precautions that should be taken, such as placing the spare battery in a plasticbag to protect it from shorting and removing metal objects before placing it in a carry-on bag.
